It looks rather elegant but it's not very good. This isn't a bug perse (just 'return 0;' would be a legal, if hopelessly inefficient, implementation of hashCode(); the only rule is that 2 equal objects have the same hashCode, it is not necessary for 2 different objects to NOT have the same hashCode, but things are far more efficient if collisions are kept to a minimum of course), but it is bordering on one and perhaps fixable.

Back to that hashCodeImpl method: Almost all guava collections end up calling this. For example, ImmutableMultimap ends up here, so does ImmutableMap, so does HashBiMap, and that's 3 out of 3 as far as looking at guava collections go.

The complaints are twofold:
- Any amount of null in the set is as if they didn't exist (They contribute '0' to the hashCode and do not mutate the already built up state of the hashCode either). In other words, take any guava collection that has this as backing hash impl and get its hashcode. Now mutate this collection by adding any number of null references into at, at any position. Take another hashCode. It'll be equal to the first one.
- Position is generally irrelevant or if it is relevant, does not mutate hashes much. a,b,c,d often has the same hashcode as c,a,b,d. 

Here's a self-contained test case that shows off a couple of collisions:

import com.google.common.collect._;
import java.util._;

public class TheLargeGuavaCollider {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public static void main(String[] args) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Multimap&lt;String, String> mmAdbc = ImmutableMultimap.of("a", "d", "b", "c");
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Multimap&lt;String, String> mmBacd = ImmutableMultimap.of("b", "a", "c", "d");
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;System.out.printf("Multimap clash: a->d, b->c (hash: %d) collides with b->a c->d (hash: %d): equal: %b%n",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;mmAdbc.hashCode(), mmBacd.hashCode(), mmAdbc.equals(mmBacd));

```
    Map<String, String> smAb = ImmutableMap.of("a", "b");
    Map<String, String> smBa = ImmutableMap.of("b", "a");
    System.out.printf("simple map clash: a->b (hash: %d) collides with b->a (hash: %d): equal: %b%n",
        smAb.hashCode(), smBa.hashCode(), smAb.equals(smBa));

    BiMap<String, String> bimapWithValues = HashBiMap.create();
    BiMap<String, String> bimapWithValuesAndNull = HashBiMap.create();
    bimapWithValues.put("a", "b");
    bimapWithValuesAndNull.put("a", "b");
    bimapWithValuesAndNull.put(null, null);
    System.out.printf("adding nulls never changes hashes: bimap with a<->b (hash: %d) vs. bimap with both a<->b and null<-> null (hash: %d): equal: %b%n",
        bimapWithValues.hashCode(), bimapWithValuesAndNull.hashCode(), bimapWithValues.equals(bimapWithValuesAndNull));
