suggested solution: Do what project lombok / eclipse auto-gen / effective java do:

before mixing in an element of hashcode from a member entity, first multiply the already existing hash code by some random convenient prime number. Also, try to avoid 0 where possible. So, something like:

&nbsp;&nbsp;static int hashCodeImpl(Set<?> s) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;int hashCode = 0;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for (Object o : s) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;hashCode = hashCode \* 349 + (o != null ? o.hashCode() : 797);
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return hashCode;
&nbsp;&nbsp;}

NB: Just changing hashes around is going to cause some issues. I pray nobody hardcoded any, but even if no guava uses did that, it also 'breaks' any hashcodes stored on disk. If any guava classes cache hashcodes and these caches aren't dynamically regenerated after a serialize/deserialize operation, this would break the equals/hashCode contract when trying to compare a deserialized (from older code) collection with an otherwise equivalent one built from scratch. Then again, even java.lang.String went through a change in hashcode definition for performance improvements and surely it can never get more painful than that.

NB2: The internals of those collections where order is defined to be irrelevant need some extra care. For example, ImmutableMultimap("a", "b", "c", "d") and ImmutableMultimap("c", "d", "a", "b") are actually equivalent (.equals() those and it'll be true). Whether this is a good idea or not is debatable (they toString() differently; they are backed by LinkedHashMaps and thus preserve insertion order), but if they are, then their hashCodes should also be equal. This should possibly be documented, and hashCode will need to adapt to take this into account.

A hashCode implementation that is better than what guava has now and maintains order independence would not just mix key and value in straight up, but would multiply the value by some prime and the key with some different prime, and would not use 0 for nulls but yet another prime. Basically, eliminate the *349 in the above snippet and it'll be order independent, with fewer ways to cause collisions.

